50|$|The {{nitrogen}} compound <b>sal</b> <b>ammoniac</b> (ammonium chloride) was known {{since the time}} of the Ancient Egyptians. In the 1760s two scientists, Henry Cavendish and Joseph Priestley, isolated nitrogen from air, but neither realized the presence of an undiscovered element. It was not until several years later, in 1772, that Daniel Rutherford realized that the gas was indeed nitrogen.|$|E
